<TEXT>
the senate on friday beat back a series of 
unrelated amendments to a catchall tax bill including one designed 
to benefit 2 million owners of home satellite dishes 
but consideration of such proposals delayed until next week 
final action on the tax bill which includes a bill of rights 
for taxpayers involved in disputes with the internal revenue 
service and special relief worth 27 billion over three years for 
various groups including farmers artists and firsttime 
homebuyers 
by nightfall an angry majority leader sen robert c byrd 
dwva counted more than 100 proposed amendments still awaiting 
action and coaxed the senate into cutting off any more 
this list is crazy nuts and getting crazier all the time 
byrd said we ought to settle down and get our senses 
within two hours byrd announced senators had agreed to drop all 
but 29 
republican leader bob dole of kansas sided with byrd noting 
amendments dealing with everything but taxes including sanctions 
against iraq aid to the nicaragua rebels and a move to halt 
commercial development of the historic manassas battlefield in 
virginia 
this is the typical tax bill dole said everybody cleans 
out their desks and their trash cans and says well put it on the 
tax bill weve reached the point that if somebody doesnt take 
the bull by the horns well never finish 
on the manassas battlefield issue the senate voted 5025 to 
approve an amendment by sen dale bumpers dark requiring the 
federal government to seize 540 acres of land to prevent further 
development on the site about 30 miles west of washington the 
house has approved the same provision but the interior secretary 
has said he will recommend that president reagan veto it 
in siding with bumpers the senate defeated a plan by sen john 
warner rva to authorize the taking of only 80 acres and allow 
development of housing on adjacent areas 
the tax bills main purpose is to correct errors in the big tax 
overhaul enacted in 1986 but since this is the only tax bill with 
a chance of becoming law this year senators view it as the last 
opportunity to have their pet amendments considered 
but there is no assurance it will become law the version 
approved by the house is considerably different and there is some 
doubt that the house and senate can negotiate a compromise before 
quitting next week 
in a long day of debate over the bill the senate considered and 
rejected amendments calling for 
an end to what sen albert gore jr dtenn called 
discrimination against owners of home satellite dishes by 
television programmers his amendment was aimed at helping the 2 
million dish owners most of them living in rural areas whose 
television and satellite dish have become prime sources of contact 
with the outside world 
gores amendment would have required that programs provided to 
cable systems be made available to dish owners and ordered the 
federal communications commission to extend network programming 
into isolated areas that cannot receive broadcast signals 
opponents led by sen daniel inouye dhawaii said the 
amendment was unnecessary that there are no unfair trade 
practices in pricing and distribution of satellite programming 
managers of the bill said gores amendment had no chances of 
becoming law as part of the tax legislation 
an 18month study of whether government workers should get 
equal pay for jobs of comparable worth sen daniel evans rwash 
proposed the study and was opposed vigorously by conservatives who 
said it would lead to new federal requirements for what any worker 
could be paid evans called the dissent blind opposition to 
knowledge 
a symbolic endorsement of the right of the district of columbia 
to finance abortions for poor women 
raising from 17 a month to 38 the maximum taxfree 
masstransit benefits that an employer could furnish workers sen 
alfonse damato rny offered the amendment in the name of 
fairness saying the government already provides a much higher 
subsidy for corporate executives to park their limousines he would 
have paid for the change by doubling to a maximum of 7700 the 
tax imposed on gasguzzling cars most of them luxury imports 
