<TEXT>
congress is moving to slap controls on medical 
waste from the vials of aidsinfected blood washing up on atlantic 
coast beaches to the used hypodermic needles picked out of trash 
bins by children in the midwest 
the vehicle to attack the growing problem of carelessly 
discarded medical waste is a bill that would require a sofar 
reluctant environmental protection agency to set up a system to 
track the waste from creation to disposal 
the legislation given impetus by this summers publicized cases 
of infectious materials littering ocean and great lakes shorelines 
was passed by the house on thursday by a 39028 margin 
the senate has approved a more limited control blueprint 
lawmakers in both chambers say they see no difficulty working out a 
joint product that can be sent to president reagan before congress 
adjourns next week 
rep thomas luken dohio says action is needed because the 
illegal disposal of medical waste is spreading like an epidemic 
across the country this waste is not just repulsive it can 
literally kill people 
according to recent federal studies as many as 18000 people 
each year may contract hepatitis b from accidental contact with 
medical waste he told the house hundreds of those infected 
will ultimately die from the infection 
the house plan would cover waste produced by hospitals clinics 
and labs in new jersey connecticut and the great lakes states of 
new york pennsylvania ohio indiana illinois michigan 
wisconsin and minnesota 
the program however could become national in scope because any 
other state could decide to have its waste covered by the plan and 
gain authority to act against incoming waste not meeting the 
tracking systems requirements 
this is a national problem said rep ron wyden dore 
the medical waste system in this country is broken it is 
overloaded and in effect it is starting to regurgitate what it 
cannot keep down 
expected to form the basis for the final bill the house plan 
would apply to 10 types of medical waste including blood 
hypodermic needles scalpels and surgical and laboratory waste that 
has been in contact with infectious agents 
the enumerated items would have to be segregated from other 
medical waste the tracking system would have to contain assurances 
that a generator knows the waste reached a disposal facility 
the legislation does not however set any standards for actual 
disposal such as burning or using a hazardous waste landfill 
supporters said there was no time this year to work out these 
details they add however that it already is illegal to dump such 
waste into waterways 
violators of the tracking requirements could be slapped with a 
civil fine of up to 25000 for each day of violation and a maximum 
criminal penalty of two years in prison and a fine of up to 50000 
per day of violation 
luken said the medical waste problem goes beyond the beach 
foulings that closed stretches of oceanfront in new york and new 
jersey the past two summers 
last year careless doctors in youngstown ohio and 
indianapolis put contaminated needles and vials of infected blood 
into dumpsters he said kids found the needles and blood vials 
and played doctor with them splattering blood on each other and 
giving each other injections that could have proved fatal 
house members said they believe epa already has the authority to 
act against medical trash under various hazardous waste control 
laws 
in 1978 the agency announced plans to regulate medical waste 
but six years later it said lacked evidence those wastes were 
causing enough harm to justify regulations 
instead epa released a package of advice to hospitals on 
handling and disposal since then epa has formed a task force to 
rethink the issue 
epa has dragged its feet on this matter wyden said epa 
told us that as of this summer they had budgeted exactly one staff 
position to deal with the medical waste issue that is why we need 
this legislation 
</TEXT>
