<TEXT>
a new recipe has been developed for fortifying 
mothers milk to help premature babies barely bigger than a mans 
hand survive and grow normally the agriculture department said 
the immune properties found in mothers milk are so much more 
important to preterm infants because they are subject to many more 
infections than fullterm infants said dr richard j schanler 
physician in charge of the project at the childrens nutrition 
research center at houston 
but extremely premature babies some of them weighing less than 
two pounds at birth require more concentrated nutrients than 
mothers milk provides he said 
most currently get a preemie formula based on cows milk until 
they reach about three pounds and are growing well after that 
some may be switched to mothers milk mixed with a commercial 
fortifier 
concern about the practice of feeding the formulas to the tiny 
infants during their first month of life prompted schanler and a 
former colleague dr cutberto garza now at cornell university to 
look into ways of using breast milk from birth 
their research at the center which is based at baylor college 
of medicine and is funded by usdas agricultural research service 
included tests of commercial formulas and new recipe possibilities 
the work was described in a report issued thursday by the agency 
schanler said the new recipe includes mineral salts that are 
readily absorbed by the infants and protein and energy from 
powdered skim mothers milk supplied by the centers own human milk 
bank 
although the recipe is being used for research purposes 
schanler said he doubts whether it will be feasible to produce a 
commercial fortifier made from human milk noting that there arent 
many human milk banks for this purpose 
but he said the findings from the recipe research should lead to 
better fortifiers so that very lowbirthweight infants can have 
the infection fighting factors present in breast milk when they 
most need it right after birth 
the milk would still have to be taken from the mother with a 
breast pump fortified with the forumla and fed to the baby through 
a tube 
the initial concern has been to get enough protein and energy 
into the tiny babies and we didnt pay much attention to 
minerals schanler said 
calcium and phosphorous were the main problem a lack of which 
could compromise growth impair healing of chronic lung disease 
and lead to bone malformations schanler said 
the scientists came close to matching the inthewomb 
retention levels of these minerals by adding calcium lactate and 
sodium or potassium phosphate to mothers milk 
infants averaging only 22 pounds at birth retained 86 percent 
of the calcium and 80 percent of the phosphorous they would have 
retained if still in their mothers uterus and are the best rates 
we have seen schanler said 
according to garza who now directs nutritional sciences at 
cornell the governments food and drug administration requires 
formula companies to add a minimum amount of calcium without 
sufficient regard to its form 
thats not enough for these tiny infants garza said you 
need to look at the form as well as the amount 
for example garza said the calcium salt added to commercial 
formulas is tribasic calcium phosphate which is not very soluble 
its like rock he said most of it probably doesnt get 
absorbed into the infants system but comes out in the stool 
calcium lactate is much better utilized 
although the scientists recognize that human milk has less 
calcium and phosphorous than both regular and preemie formulas 
they say the minerals are in a form more easily absorbed by the 
infants also human milk may have unknown factors that enhance 
infants absorption and retention 
formula companies have not been able to duplicate these 
conditions in commercial preparations and compensate by increasing 
the concentration of minerals the report said 
another former colleague dr steven a abrams a physician now 
at the national institutes of health said the higher 
concentrations of minerals in commercial formulas may benefit the 
very lowbirthweight infants after they leave the hospital 
after discharge the mothers either chose to continue on 
unfortified breast milk or switch to regular infant formula 
abrams who tracked the infants for a year found that the 
breastfed babies had a lower bone mineral content than those who 
got commerical formulas 
but they grew equally well on either he said body weight 
length and head measurements were the same for both groups 
abrams recommended that pediatricians regularly evaluate the 
mineral status of nursing preemies but he added that the risks 
do not outweigh the benefits of breast feeding 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

