<TEXT>
a proposed federal regulation to require 
regular drug testing of atomic plant workers is under attack on 
capitol hill for lacking similar standards to curb alcohol abuse 
the nuclear regulatory commission announced a proposed fitness 
for duty rule last month that would require reactor owners to 
conduct random drug tests test employees based on cause report 
drug use to the nrc and mandate personnel sanctions 
the proposal also would require utilities to submit their own 
alcohol programs providing reasonable assurance that plant 
operators are sober but leaves to the discretion of each 
licensee the specific measures to be used nrc chairman lando w 
zech jr said thursday 
it is as if the nrc is saying that it is less concerned with 
someone being drunk in the control room than it is with someone 
being high on drugs said rep sam gejdenson dconn chairman 
of the house interior and insular affairs subcommittee on oversight 
and investigations 
gejdenson and other lawmakers have long urged the nrc to impose 
strict drug and alcohol standards instead of leaving it up 
individual utilities 
zech under heavy criticism from both democrats and republicans 
on the subcommittee stressed that the fitness for duty rule 
was simply a proposal and could be changed to include specific 
alcohol standards before it is issued next year 
but he defended the commissions decision to remove strict 
alcohol provisions that were in earlier drafts of the regulation 
zech said it was more difficult to develop a consensus on 
alcohol standards than drug restrictions noting the different 
blood alcohol levels used by various states and federal agencies to 
determine inebriation 
trying to include specific alcohol requirements in the rule 
could have delayed the final regulation another few months or 
maybe longer zech said 
but lawmakers were befuddled and angered by that explanation 
youre sitting around and waiting for utility companies to 
tell you how to do it said rep george miller dcalif dont 
you have some idea what the minimum standard ought to be this is 
not a new subject 
rep denny smith of oregon a republican who is often at odds 
with the democrats criticism agreed with miller and gejdenson 
i think your judgment needs to be questioned he told the 
commissioners it just doesnt make sense not to include the 
alcohol provision he said 
gejdenson pointed to an nrc document that concluded that alcohol 
abuse and drinkingrelated problems are judged to present a 
vastly more pervasive work place problem than does drug abuse 
zech said he agreed with that statement but another 
commissioner said drug abuse presented a bigger problem than 
