cuba angola and south africa held 
informal talks friday on plans for south africa to end its rule 
over neighboring southwest africa and for cuba to withdraw about 
50000 troopers from angola 
chester crocker us undersecretary of state for african 
affairs mediated the talks continuing the role he played in 
meetings earlier this year in brazzaville the congo according to 
american and south african officials 
aubry dwyer a spokesman for south africas un mission 
confirmed the talks were being held he said the south african 
delegation was led by neil van heerden directorgeneral of 
political affairs 
no announcement was expected at the conclusion of the talks and 
officials did not say where the negotiations were being held other 
than they were in new york 
dwyer said the talks dealt with a timetable for the withdrawal 
of the cuban military personnel in line with the nov 1 deadline 
south africa accepted for beginning a plan for independence for 
southwest africa also known as namibia 
south africa insists the cubans should be removed from 
marxistruled angola in about a year 
in earlier rounds of talks cuba and angola first said the 
withdrawal would take four years then lowered that to three and 
last month reportedly accepted a proposal for a twoyear phased 
withdrawal 
officials involved in the talks have expressed confidence a 
mutually acceptable timetable will be worked out during the next 
formal meeting of the four parties in brazzaville 
no date has been set for those talks but they presumably would 
be held before the nov 1 date for south africa to begin 
implementing un resolution 435 passed 10 years ago calling for 
independence for namibia 
the united nations plans to send a peacekeeping force of 7500 
military personnel and 2000 members of a civilian support staff to 
oversee elections for a national assembly in namibia 
a un advance team is now in namibia checking on housing 
airports and other facilities the peacekeepers will need un 
officials have estimated the peacekeeping force to be called the 
un transition assistance group will cost 600 million to 700 
million 
south africa has administered namibia under a mandate from the 
defunct league of nations since the end of world war i 
the un general assembly and security council have revoked the 
mandate and declared south africas administration illegal 
namibia is located between south africa and angola which 
received independence from portugal in 1975 marxist forces 
defeated prowestern groups in a civil war following independence 
but rebels of the union for total independence for angola 
supported by south africa and the united states have waged 
guerrilla warfare against the government and cuba sent troops into 
angola to help battle the rebels 
