<TEXT>
an underground coal fire discovered by 
children when sticks they poked into the ground caught fire has 
been extinguished by firefighters with water and synthetic foam 
into holes bored into the earth 
no houses in the southeast ohio city of 5000 people were 
damaged by the fire which had covered a 40by40foot area but it 
had threatened as many as 30 homes 
we were lucky to get to it in its infancy fire chief tim 
baden said friday 
the burning material waste coal believed to have come from an 
unmapped mine abandoned in the 1920s was 4 feet deep it was 
discovered sept 30 
on wednesday and thursday firefighters drilled holes about the 
size of fire extinguishers into the ground to determine the area of 
the fire baden said once isolated additional holes were dug 
throughout the area and water was poured into them 
that is a quenching effect the quenching essentially would 
take away the heat the chief said 
after another dousing of water firefighters capped the holes 
with a synthetic material which baden described as a type of 
firefighting foam used to fight oil fires by smothering them 
what that essentially does is knock out the oxygen that way 
we keep all the oxygen out of it baden said 
officials determined after additional core samples taken friday 
that the fire died out 
baden said the fire entered a coal seam and could have burned 
indefinitely had it not been extinguished immediately 
