<TEXT>
chinese officials have announced tough new 
measures to halt construction projects targeted in an upcoming 
nationwide crackdown on what the government considers excessive 
capital investment which officials blame for high inflation 
after dec 1 authorities will withhold bank loans energy and 
building supplies and construction licenses from targeted projects 
to force them to close down the official peoples daily reported 
friday 
the newspaper quoted senior official chen guangjian newly 
appointed by premier li peng to spearhead efforts to curb capital 
construction 
he said projects slated for cancellation include those that rely 
on imported or scarce domestic raw materials are underfinanced 
will produce highenergyconsuming goods or goods that are already 
made in excess 
aside from a handful of projects already approved by the state 
planning commission construction will be halted on all office 
buildings auditoriums and hotels begun this year no new building 
will be allowed for two to three years he said 
according to a china daily report chen said projects which use 
imported technology and foreign funding are expected to escape 
cutting 
capital investment has grown at a rate of 188 percent over the 
past three years far outstripping the 164 percent rate of 
increase in national income during the same period the toorapid 
rate of investment has helped fuel an inflation rate currently 
about 20 percent 
chen said blind emphasis on shortterm profits in enterprises as 
well as the failure of local banks to abide by state loan quotas 
and policies were responsible for investment inflation 
the central committee of the communist party launched an attack 
on inflation and confusion in the economy in its plenary session 
last week criticizing party members and local officials for lax 
discipline in carrying out its economic policies 
the central government has led repeated drives with little 
success against excessive capital investment including a partial 
halt on hotel and theater construction earlier this year 
leaders intend the current campaign to be allinclusive in 
scope subjecting all capital investment nationwide to close 
scrutiny 
