<TEXT>
first fridays are proving to be full of mostly 
pleasant surprises for the bond market but some analysts see 
turbulence ahead 
for the past two months the first friday has meant reassurance 
for bondholders worried that the economy may be growing so fast 
that inflation will accelerate and take a heavy toll on the value 
of their fixedincome securities 
the first friday of each month is when the government reports on 
the employment situation in the previous month providing the most 
current official glimpse of the state of the economy 
the reports for august and september have indicated to many 
analysts that the economy is growing at a moderate yet still 
healthy pace 
more important each of the reports was viewed as reducing 
chances that the federal reserve would feel compelled to encourage 
higher interest rates 
this past friday the government reported that the september 
unemployment rate slipped to 54 percent from 56 percent the 
previous month most bond traders focused on payroll employment 
growth though and the september increase of 255000 jobs fell 
45000 short of expectations 
the reaction was immediate prices jumped and trading volume 
swelled after slowing to a trickle in the past few days in 
anticipation of the report 
by midafternoon the price of the 30year treasury bond was up 
more than 15 for every 1000 in face value and its yield was at 
880 percent its lowest level since midapril 
the rally was not quite as strong as the one that followed the 
release of the august unemployment figures which saw the 
unemployment rate rise to 56 percent from 54 percent in july and 
payroll growth of 219000 
bonds staged one of their biggest advances of the year that day 
with some 30year treasury issues rising more than 25 for every 
1000 in face value 
