<TEXT>
freight companies hauling iron ore coal and 
other heavy cargo through the great lakes say the summer drought 
pulled the plug on their shipping season by lowering water levels 
but a us army corps of engineers official said friday the 
firms shouldnt blame the hot weather for failing to keep up with 
heavy demands 
the clevelandbased lake carriers association will ask the 
corps to give them an extra month to haul cargo through locks at 
sault ste marie in michigans upper peninsula 
the four locks which link lake superior to lake michigan and 
the industrylined st lawrence seaway normally close from dec 
15 until april 1 when ice clogs the lakes 
shipping giants such as american steamship co say evaporation 
from the drought lowered water levels forcing ships to lighten 
their cargoes they want to use the sault ste marie locks until at 
least jan 15 lake carriers association spokesman glen nekvasil 
said friday 
the extension would give american steamship and the groups 13 
other shipping firms time to make extra trips and catch up with an 
increasing demand for raw materials nekvasil said 
fleets have been hard pressed to meet current demand he 
said adding that increased steel production has boosted 1988 
shipments by more than 13 percent 
freight companies may need more time to keep pace with 
shipments but they shouldnt blame the drought for their problems 
corps spokesman donald billmaier said 
i dont think they hurt much from the drought i just think 
theyve got more business said billmaier chief of operations 
and maintenance for the corps detroit district 
billmaier confirmed that water levels have dropped over the past 
year but said shipping companies compensated earlier by hauling 
heavier loads when the water was deeper 
they cant haul loads as big as they could two years ago 
thats true he said maybe they cant make as much money but 
they can still work the lakes 
billmaier said the corps which controls the upper peninsula 
locks also restricts winter shipping in an effort to minimize 
environmental damage 
ships maneuvering through ice jams cause extra water turbulence 
that kills fish damages docks and shoreline and disturbs the 
bottom of the great lakes he said 
billmaier said the corps chicago bureau probably will agree to 
extend the shipping season by at least two weeks if carriers can 
prove they need the extra time he could not predict when a final 
ruling will be made 
